<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-162-908  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 162 908.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  April 3 1989 v23 n14 p100(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Strong scruples can curb computer crime. (includes related articleon the FBI's computer crime efforts)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Alexander, Michael.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Larry Potts, chief of the white-collar crimes program of the FBI,claims that while the laws regarding computer crime in the US arerelatively strong, the ethics of citizens regarding computer useare not.andP;  This attitude encourages computer-related crimes.andP;  Manypeople believe that computer crimes are victimless.andP;  Until theethics of the situation are reinforced and computer crimes areassociated with the same disdain people now hold for robbery,these crimes will continue.andP;  Only increased security precautionswill deter hackers until law enforcement agencies become betterequipped to handle these cases or until society changes itsperceptions of the crimes.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     United States. Federal Bureau of InvestigationComputer CrimeEthicsUser BehaviorLaw enforcement.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andO;Person:    Potts, Larry (attitudes).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>